text.tspan: Parliamentary constituencies are sorted according to the relative deprivation of the area using data from the Index of Multiple Deprivation 2019, with
the most deprived constituency in the top left, and the least deprived in the bottom right.
Shapes show the relative deprivation profile of each area, with a wider bottom indicating more deprivation, and a wider top indicating less deprivation.
Parliamentary constituencies are divided into lower super output areas (LSOAs), where each LSOA has approximately 1,500 residents. There are
32,844 LSOAs in England, which are ranked according to their level of relative deprivation. These LSOAs are sorted into 20 equal sets (vigintiles) each
containing 1642 LSOAs. These are then matched with the parliamentary constituency, and the profile drawn from the amount of LSOAs in each
vigintile in the area. Some LSOAs straddle multiple constituencies. In these case, the LSOA as associated with both constituencies to draw the profile.
All profiles have been normalised so they are the same width - if we did not do this it would be difficult to see the profiles of constituences with

Data sources used: Indices of Deprivation 2019 data published by the Ministry of Housing Communities and Local Government at
